Class Assignment¶

Use Seaborn dataset for 'penguins'

  • Find simple linear reqression between bill (x) and filler lenghts (y)
  • Create a figure with the equation ##### Note: Remove the observations with NaN values!
In [37]:
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

# Load the penguins dataset from Seaborn
penguins = sns.load_dataset('penguins')

# Remove observations with NaN values
penguins_clean = penguins[['bill_length_mm', 'flipper_length_mm']].dropna()

# Extract the features (x) and target variable (y)
x = penguins_clean['bill_length_mm'].values.reshape(-1, 1)
y = penguins_clean['flipper_length_mm'].values

# Perform simple linear regression
coefficients = np.polyfit(x.flatten(), y, 1)
poly = np.poly1d(coefficients)

# Plot the data points
sns.scatterplot(x='bill_length_mm', y='flipper_length_mm', data=penguins_clean)

# Plot the regression line
x_line = np.linspace(min(x), max(x), 100)
y_line = poly(x_line)
plt.plot(x_line, y_line, color='red', label=f'Regression Line: {coefficients[0]:.2f}x + {coefficients[1]:.2f}')

# Set labels and title
plt.xlabel('Bill Length (mm)')
plt.ylabel('Flipper Length (mm)')
plt.title('Simple Linear Regression: Bill Length vs Flipper Length')

# Display the equation on the plot
equation_text = f'Equation: y = {coefficients[0]:.2f}x + {coefficients[1]:.2f}'
plt.text(50, 220, equation_text, color='red')

# Show the legend
plt.legend()

# Show the plot
plt.show()

In [46]:
# Add the regression plane in the figure
# Extract the coefficients
coef_X1, coef_X2 = model.coef_
intercept = model.intercept_
# create the figure
fig = plt.figure()
ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')
x1 = df1['carat']
x2 = df1['depth']
y = df1['price']
# Create a meshgrid for the plane
x1_plane, x2_plane = np.meshgrid(x1, x2)
y_plane = intercept + coef_X1 * x1_plane + coef_X2 * x2_plane
ax.scatter(x1, x2, y, c='b', marker='o', label='Data Points')
# plot the regression plane
ax.plot_surface(x1_plane, x2_plane, y_plane, alpha=0.5, 
                cmap='viridis', label='Regression Plane')
ax.set_xlabel('carat')
ax.set_ylabel('depth')
ax.set_zlabel('price')
plt.title('3D Scatter Plot with Regression Plane')
plt.show()

Home work¶

In [ ]:

Use Seaborn dataset for any data you are interested

Note: the dataset must contain at least three quantitative variables¶
  • Find multiple linear reqression between two independent data (X1, X2) and dependent data (y)
  • Create a 3D figure that shows also regression pane
In [48]:
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import Axes3D
import numpy as np

# Load the iris dataset from Seaborn
iris = sns.load_dataset('iris')

# Select three quantitative variables
X = iris[['sepal_length', 'sepal_width']]
y = iris['petal_length']

# Perform multiple linear regression
coefficients = np.linalg.lstsq(X, y, rcond=None)[0]

# Create a 3D plot
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')

# Scatter plot of data points
ax.scatter(X['sepal_length'], X['sepal_width'], y, c='blue', marker='o', label='Data Points')

# Create a meshgrid for the regression plane
sepal_length_range = np.linspace(X['sepal_length'].min(), X['sepal_length'].max(), 50)
sepal_width_range = np.linspace(X['sepal_width'].min(), X['sepal_width'].max(), 50)
sepal_length_grid, sepal_width_grid = np.meshgrid(sepal_length_range, sepal_width_range)
regression_plane = coefficients[0] * sepal_length_grid + coefficients[1] * sepal_width_grid

# Plot the regression plane
ax.plot_surface(sepal_length_grid, sepal_width_grid, regression_plane, alpha=0.5, color='red')

# Set labels and title
ax.set_xlabel('Sepal Length')
ax.set_ylabel('Sepal Width')
ax.set_zlabel('Petal Length')
ax.set_title('Multiple Linear Regression: Petal Length ~ Sepal Length + Sepal Width')

# Create a 2D plot for the legend
legend_ax = fig.add_axes([0.8, 0.1, 0.1, 0.1])  # Adjust the position and size as needed
legend_ax.axis('off')
legend_ax.legend(handles=[plt.Line2D([0], [0], marker='o', color='w', markerfacecolor='blue', markersize=10, label='Data Points'),
                          plt.Line2D([0], [0], color='red', linewidth=2, label='Regression Plane')])

# Display the plot
plt.show()
